post_text: Our thoughts are with Mayor Copeland's family. His impact in our city will last indefinitely. Thank you for your leadership.
shared_text:
City of Olathe, KS Government
August 20 at 11:01 AM ·

It is with a heavy heart we announce the passing of Mayor Michael Copeland.

Mayor Copeland dedicated 27 years of service in Olathe, including 19 as Mayor.

He had passion for children and helping those in need. He was also engaged in numerous boards and commissions throughout the Metro.

Mayor Copeland's service to the Olathe community will be missed.

We ask you keep his family in your thoughts and prayers.

To learn more about Mayor Copeland's legacy, visit https://www.olatheks.org/Home/Components/News/News/2957/58.

Good news? Good news!

Recently 12 Olathe high school students have been named 2020 Kansas Career and Technical Education (CTE) Scholars by the Kansas State Department of Education (KSDE).

Olivia Bond, Olathe Northwest High School; Yajaira Chaparro, Olathe North High School; Tristin Gibbins, Olathe East High School; Olivia Gray, Olathe North; Meagan Hrivnak, Olathe West High School; Zachary Inman, Olathe Northwest; Gauge Kellogg, Olathe West; Brooke Ritter, Olathe South High School; Gloria Schoenhals, Olathe North; Brennan Smith, Olathe North; Jose Antonio Aguirre Valencia, Olathe North; and Trea Stahlhut, Olathe North were named Kansas CTE scholars.

The Kansas CTE Scholar Program recognizes well-rounded, outstanding CTE students who are finishing their senior year of high school and meet the criteria provided by the KSDE.

post_text:
🚨🚨🚨 Good News Alert 🚨🚨🚨

Students at Mill Creek Campus were awarded the Help My MoKan Schools Grant provided by 99.7 The Point, Sheet Metal Workers Local Union No. 2 and SMACNA.

This grant is $15,000 and it will provide two new projects to the Mill Creek Campus. First it will aide in designing a Student Wellness Center which empowers students to strive for balance and wellness. Secondly, part of the grant would be used for a small business incubator designed to promote entrepreneurship, real world learning and 21st century skills.

“We want our students to have opportunities that prepare them for life after high school, “ Mill Creek facilitator Deb Jaeger said. “We focus on building relationships with community partners, learning skills that will prepare them for a career and providing them with experiences that will equip them to be successful in the future. Our students will leave high school with a diploma and market value assets.”

post_text:
The Olathe South High School theatre program earned the Outstanding School Award from Education Theatre Association. This award is given annually to theatre programs that exemplify and promote high standards in educational theatre. This is the second time Olathe South has received the award and the third time a school in the Olathe School District has earned the award since the accolade was established in 1992.

“I am very proud of the students at Olathe South that have helped us earn this award,” Olathe South theatre director David Hastings said. “I hope our students see this as a validation of their work. This achievement is just another way that our students are prepared for their future.”
text:
The Olathe South High School theatre program earned the Outstanding School Award from Education Theatre Association. This award is given annually to theatre programs that exemplify and promote high standards in educational theatre. This is the second time Olathe South has received the award and the third time a school in the Olathe School District has earned the award since the accolade was established in 1992.

“I am very proud of the students at Olathe South that have helped us earn this award,” Olathe South theatre director David Hastings said. “I hope our students see this as a validation of their work. This achievement is just another way that our students are prepared for their future.”

At the March Olathe Public Schools Board of Education meeting, a long-standing business partner, students and staff members were recognized:

Robert Brogden Buick GMC is a longtime supporter of the district with donations to the Olathe Public Schools Foundation Wimmer Student Care Fund which supports students facing economic challenges. Brogden also supports district events and most recently as a sponsor for video boards at the district athletic centers. Recently, the Robert Brogden service staff partnered with the Olathe Advanced Technical Center as students prepared for the National Automotive Technicians Educational Foundation accreditation visit.

Bennett Johnson, a music teacher at Heritage Elementary School, is one of 32 Horizon Award Winners in Kansas.

Andrea Shehi of Olathe East High School and Dylan Stanley of Olathe South High School achieved perfect scores on the ACT exam.

Congratulations on your honors!

This afternoon Pioneer Trail Middle School held a surprise assembly to send well wishes to Marco Romero. Tomorrow Romero will travel to Colorado Springs, CO, to attend the USA Boxing's Junior Boys Prep Training Camp before competing in the Emil Jechev Memorial Tournament in Botevgrad, Bulgaria from March 13-22.

Romero is the 2019 National Boxing Champion as a welterweight on the Junior Olympic Team.

A banner for Romero will be hung in the gym with Pioneer Trail's athletic banners. Students wrote notes to Romero in advance of his trip.

Best of luck to Romero!

This morning Olathe North High School alum and recently retired NFL great Darren Sproles visited Central Elementary and spoke to students about setting goals, resiliency and working hard.

Students recently submitted essays regarding perseverance and those that received honorable mention were recognized. Students who won their age group will receive personal visits.

Guest speakers included Superintendent John Allison and members of the Board of Education and former Olathe North football coach Gene Weir.

Mayor Copeland gave Sproles a key to the city as a token of appreciation for his work with students and in the Olathe community.

Thank you to Darren Sproles for all that you've done in Olathe and across the country. Congratulations on a Hall of Fame career.

post_text:
At the February Board of Education meeting, the following groups and individuals were recognized for their achievements and support:

Garmin is a valued community partner. As part of their long-standing partnership, Garmin provides support and educational initiatives including the implementation of a new STEM program, proving staff to help with elementary coding activities, hosting an Olathe Public Schools Foundation Women’s Giving Circle event and much more.

Baptist Trinity Lutheran Legacy Foundation provides grants for student health-related events.

Samantha Collins, an English/Language Arts teacher at Chisholm Trail Middle School, is a Kansas Horizon Award winner.

David Hastings, Olathe South High School theater director, was inducted into the Kansas Thespians Hall of Fame.

Congratulations!

#MyOlatheSchools

post_text:
As the Super Bowl is Sunday and features the hometown The Kansas City Chiefs, multiple Olatheans have had a successful history representing their hometown of Olathe in the Super Bowl:

- Don Davis (Olathe South alum) earned two Super Bowl rings as a player in Super Bowl XXXVIII and Super Bowl XXXIX.
- Darren Sproles (Olathe North alum) earned a Super Bowl ring as a member of the Philadelphia Eagles in Super Bowl LII (2018).
- Nate Weir (Olathe South alum) was a member of the training staff for the 2010 Super Bowl Champion Green Bay Packers.
- Sophie Schneider (Olathe West student) delivered the game ball to the head referee at Super Bowl LI (2017).
- Josh Umphrey (Olathe West assistant principal) will be taking photos on the sideline of Super Bowl LIV (2020) as a professional photographer.

#TriviaTuesday x #MyOlatheSchools x #OlatheMade
